What are the major complications of meningitis?
Major complications of meningitides include: 1. Brain injury - Damage to brain tissue caused by lack of oxygen can result in intellectual disability, seizures, and motor problems. 2. Hearing loss - Both temporary and permanent hearing loss can occur due to inflammation in the inner ear. 3. Intellectual disability - Meningitis can lead to long-term mental retardation. 4. Seizures - Inflammation of the brain can cause seizures. 5. Stroke - In severe cases of meningitis, blood clots can form, leading to stroke. 6. Brain herniation - Increased pressure in the brain can lead to brain tissue being pushed into adjacent areas, which can be fatal. 7. Heart problems - Some strains of bacteria that cause meningitis can also affect the heart, leading to pericarditis or myocarditis. 8. Kidney damage

